{"key":"post-9248038","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9248038</id>\n<content>That is the recipe if you're using calcium carbonate.&amp;nbsp; If you're using hydrated lime(which I recommend) use it at a starting rate of 1 teaspoon per cup of peat.&amp;nbsp; Your after hydration pH will be in the 8 to 9 range, and within 24 hours will drop to around 7.5 to 8.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you used one cup of hydrated lime per 15 cups of peat, that's too much.&amp;nbsp; I'd double the peat and measure pH again.&amp;nbsp; Be sure to let it sit for an hour or two before measuring.&amp;nbsp; In addition, if you'll add up to ten percent gypsum, it will bring the pH down a tad also.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9248048</next>\n<prev>9248015</prev>\n<first>9247983</first>\n<last>9248048</last>\n<when>1226764567</when>\n<utime>11/15/08 05:56 PM</utime>\n</post>"}